[DhtmlXQ_comment0]sg 20120917 1999 ncsc GM Xu Yinchuan D GM Liu Dianzhong C23 ||ECCO C23 Central cannon with pawn ranked chariot and 7th filed horse vs Screen Horse Defense with Double headed snake pawn formation.||ECCO:C23 ???????????????||||Jim: Special thanks must be given to Chris Hanksinson for donating this game!!! Comments are by GM Liu Dianzhong himself and Chris has done a nice job of translating. I have added footnotes to help the beginner understand where necessary.||||This game was played in the fifth round of the National Individual Championship, each player having ??2.5 points fromt he first 4 rounds, and now the two leaders meet for a bitter struggle.[/DhtmlXQ_comment0]
[DhtmlXQ_comment4]Black plays P7+1. Since the Guandong players are very fond of the 5 7 Cannon variation with 3rd soldier advanced, it is a good idea to avoid it![/DhtmlXQ_comment4]
[DhtmlXQ_comment23]Red traverses the chariot to force and exchange early. ||I had played this variatin against Shenzhen's Master Liu Xing back in 1997.||It seemed that the Guangdong team had taken note of this variation and after much study and improvisions, it became quite a lethal weapon for them, producing good results.[/DhtmlXQ_comment23]
[DhtmlXQ_comment26]In this years championships (1999), in the second round, there had been two similar games played with this variation. ||Please click on the variations to see them... ||In this game, I chose to play R1=4. In retrospect, it would not seem as a very mature concept. A better move would still be C8+2, to wait for red to play E7+5 and then advance my horse H3+4.[/DhtmlXQ_comment26]
[DhtmlXQ_comment28]Black advances the horse for an exchange. ||This would be a better move than R4+6!||Click on the variation to understand why.[/DhtmlXQ_comment28]
[DhtmlXQ_comment31]Prior to the game, I had not dismissed the possibility that GM Xu would use this variation. So, after some study, I designed the H6+4 variation. Unfortunately, it did not produce the results that I had hoped.||The main reason was that I had conceived of this variation 15 minutes prior to the game and was unable to contemplate the variation in greater depth.||I believe the crucial factor was the way red had played the elephant. In my mind, I had expected that red would play E7+5 instead of E3+5.||If indeed black had played E7+5, I could have chosen to continue with C8+5...||(Please click on the variation below to understand what went through GM Liu's mind...)||But in the actual game, GM Xu played this elephant instead!||||    ????????????????????????,?????????6?4???,????????????????,????1 5????,??????????????????????,????????????,?????8?5,????5?4???,???????????????,?????8?5,??????,???5?4,?????????,????????????????????????,???????????,?????[/DhtmlXQ_comment31]
[DhtmlXQ_comment32]But in the actual game, GM Xu played this elephant instead! If I had continued with C8+5 ...||(Please click on the variation to understand what GM Liu was concerned about...)||That is why, in the actual game, I chose P3+1, for the chariot exchange.||That lead to my cannon and chariot being pinned by  red's chariot and I was on the receiving end going into the endgame.[/DhtmlXQ_comment32]
[DhtmlXQ_comment38]With this move, black tries to free himself from red's pin with a possible R8=7 to exchange cannon for horse, thereby simplifying the game.||This was perhaps the most crucial move in this game, a move that would decide the outcome.[/DhtmlXQ_comment38]
[DhtmlXQ_comment50]After some hard work, red achieved more space to maneuver this chess pieces and was now prepared to concentrate his chess pieces to oppress black's room to move.||In retrospect, P9+1 would seem to be a bad move as trying to protect this pawn would actually increase the difficulty of forcing a draw! ||Black should have played H6-7 and try to play H9+7. It would have been easier that way.[/DhtmlXQ_comment50]
[DhtmlXQ_comment54]Red read the game accurately and with this move, red had prevented black from playing H6-7 to try to give his cannon a root.||This turn of events placed much pressure on black and the gravity and implications were severe.||Black was thus forced to retreat the horse out of desperation.||If black had one retreated his horse, red could have played P5+1 and the black horse would be left  with even less room to maneuver. ||Jim: It would become a sitting horse (or duck if you insist)...[/DhtmlXQ_comment54]
